dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.1",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 1 : Basic Controls

Here's the list of possible commands
to use in the game :

- Action (Space) allows various
interactions (talk, run,
carry, swim, ...).
- Roll (Space) allows you to do
a roll, which allows you
to move quickly.
- Attack (C) allows you to attack
with the sword. By holding the
button, you can charge
your sword. You can then
tap walls or perform a
circular attack by releasing.
- Item 1/2 (X/V) allows you to
use an item assigned
to one of these keys.
- Pause (D) allows you to put the
game on pause and navigate between
various menus.
- Save (Escape) allows you to
save the game. You
can then choose to
continue your game or not.
Don't forget that every adventurer
must rest regularly !
- Look around (S) allows you to
look beyond the limits
of the camera by moving it.
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.2",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 2 : Pause Menus :
Inventory
By pressing Pause, you
will open by default the
Inventory menu.
This menu contains assignable items.
You can move your cursor to these
items and decide to use them
by assigning them to Item 1/2.

Some items such as bags
will open. You can then
view their contents and
assign the items containing
them to use or show them
to the inhabitants of the world.
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.3",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 3 : Other pause menus
The Inventory is not the only
pause menu. By going to
the extreme left/right with
your cursor, you can
switch to other menus.

Know that there are also
shortcut keys for some
menus :
- A will open the Map menu.
- Q will open the Commands menu.
These keys can be modified.
The Quest Status menu contains
various information regarding
your quest progression.
It includes quest items.
They usually indicate your
progression in various
main or side quests.

You can also consult
statistics related to the
game : Your playtime,
your attack/defense, and your
number of deaths.

The Map menu will show the
world map and your position if
you're in the outside world.
If you're in a Dungeon, it
will show you the area map and
the Dungeon's stats.
Another menu is the Commands
menu. It will allow you
to modify the keys used
and even to play with a controller
(see chapter 5 for more
details).
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.4",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 4 : The HUD

The HUD or game interface
presents various information.

In the top left is the
health gauge and below it the
magic gauge.
In the top right are shown
the items assigned to the X and V keys, the sword icon,
and the possible actions
to perform if you press Action.

In the bottom left is listed
the current number of Rupees
and the number of small keys if
you're in a Dungeon or an area containing small keys.
In the bottom right is the
clock. This indicates the
current Time cycle.
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.5",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 5 : Customizing
commands and controller support
The detail of the commands is found
in the Commands menu.

We won't repeat them here
but we'll tell you that it's
possible to modify them.
To do so, press Action
on the desired command and
press the new key.
Good news for gamepad enthusiasts : It's possible to
play with a controller !
To assign an action to a
controller button, the method is
the same as mentioned earlier.
However, it's important to
note that any key customization
is saved
with each game file
only. If you start a
new game, you'll need to
assign your keyboard/controller
keys again.
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.6",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 6 : Giving an item
to someone
To give an item, it's not
enough to talk to the person
with the item in your pocket.
You must assign the item and
then press the assigned key
next to the person.
This may seem trivial but can
be counterintuitive for
some !
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.7",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 7 : Day/night cycle

In the world, Time passes
only in the outside world
and outside of villages.
Just stay long enough
in the same area until you hear
a sound effect.
This means that time has passed
one cycle.

In the next zone change,
Time will be in the next
cycle.

Time is divided into 6 cycles :
2 for day, 1 for evening,
2 for night, 1 for dawn.
It's advisable to visit
areas and especially
villages during day and night.
Depending on the time of day,
various events can occur.
Additional note : Sleeping in
a bed will immediately
advance to the next
day/night cycle.
]],
}

dialog{
  id = "book.tuto.8",
  skip = "all",
  text = [[
       Adventurer's Guide
Chapter 8 : Secret rooms

Each Dungeon in the world hides
at least one secret room.

These rooms are behind
walls that you can pass through.

They usually hide
money. There's allegedly
a Magnifying Glass in the world
that reveals the position of
these secret rooms.
]],
}

